\#Section 1 \#\#\#Introduction: How can I make my KickStarter campaign a
success?

\#\#\#Research questions * Are there certain types/category of campaigns
that are more successful? * How much money should you ask for? * Is
there a time period for the campaign that works better than others? *
What is the average contribution of a backer? * Is there a better time
of year to launch a campaign?

\#\#\#Approach * I will be performing basic data analysis and
correlation on the data set provided. I will review things like the
mean, median and mode of some of the factors that are of interest.

\#\#\#\#How your approach addresses (fully or partially) the problem. By
finding out which metrics matter, we can use these elements to ensure
your next kickstarter campaign ends in success.

\#\#\#\#Data \url{https://www.kaggle.com/kemical/kickstarter-projects}

\#\#\#\#Required Packages * dplyr * ggplot2 * plotly * lm.beta

\#\#\#\#Plots and Table Needs * Scatter plots * data tables *
correlation tables * box plots

\#\#\#\#Questions for future steps * Should I look into neural networks?

\section{Section 2}\label{section-2}}

\subsubsection{How to import and clean my
data}\label{how-to-import-and-clean-my-data}}

I am importing the data by connecting the the CSV that was available for
download on the Kaggle site.
\url{https://www.kaggle.com/kemical/kickstarter-projects}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# load the data}
\NormalTok{ks_df <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"D:/College/DSC520/dsc520/data/ks-projects-201801.csv"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

I am cleaning the data set to prepare it for analysis. \#\#\#\#Check for
missing columns

\#\#\#\#Check variables names

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

\KeywordTok{library}\NormalTok{(dplyr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\end{Highlighting}

Here I renamed the variable usd.pledged to usd\_pledged to align the
naming conventions of all of my headers, since the rest of the headers
uses underscores instead of periods for spaces.

\#\#\#\#Check missing observations

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# checks for missing values in observations}
\KeywordTok{colMeans}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(ks_df))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
##               ID             name         category    main_category 
##       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000 
##         currency         deadline             goal         launched 
##       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000 
##          pledged            state          backers          country 
##       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000 
##      usd_pledged usd_pledged_real    usd_goal_real            rowid 
##       0.01002744       0.00000000       0.00000000       0.00000000
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# removes column from data set}
\NormalTok{ks_df =}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{subset}\NormalTok{(ks_df, }\DataTypeTok{select =} \OperatorTok{-}\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(usd_pledged) )}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Here I am looking for missing values. There is a small amount of data in
the usd\_pledged with missing values. If I wanted to cleanse the data
set, I could remove these values, but for now, I want to keep it in mind
since there are zero missing values from usd\_pledged\_real, which is a
column giving the same information, but the conversion to USD was done
from the fixer.io api instead of done by kickstarter. Instead of
removing the rows with the missing data, I am going to remove the column
from the data set since it is a duplicate column.

usd\_pledged: conversion in US dollars of the pledged column (conversion
done by kickstarter). usd pledge real: conversion in US dollars of the
pledged column (conversion from Fixer.io API).

\hypertarget{how-do-you-plan-to-slice-and-dice-the-data.}{%
\subsubsection{How do you plan to slice and dice the
data?.}\label{how-do-you-plan-to-slice-and-dice-the-data.}}

Created a new variable for \% successful by taking the pledged and
dividing it by the goal. I also slided out the month for both deadline
and launch dates.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Adding new rows to slide and dice the data later}
\NormalTok{ks_df <-}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{ks_df }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}
    \DataTypeTok{pledged_to_goal =}\NormalTok{ usd_pledged_real}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{usd_goal_real,}
    \DataTypeTok{count =} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}
    \DataTypeTok{deadline_month =} \KeywordTok{format}\NormalTok{(deadline,}\StringTok{"%m"}\NormalTok{),}
    \DataTypeTok{launched_month =} \KeywordTok{format}\NormalTok{(launched,}\StringTok{"%m"}\NormalTok{),}
    \DataTypeTok{backers_per_pledge =}\NormalTok{ usd_pledged_real}\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{backers}
\NormalTok{    )}

\NormalTok{ks_df}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{section-3}{%
\section{Section 3}\label{section-3}}

\hypertarget{introduction}{%
\subsubsection{Introduction}\label{introduction}}

Kickstarter campaigns is a way to crowdsource funding to support
projects, people or situations. It's a way to raise money. In this
analysis, I will be finding out if there are controllable factors which
can lead to a successful campaign.

\hypertarget{the-problem-statement-you-addressed}{%
\subsubsection{The problem statement you
addressed}\label{the-problem-statement-you-addressed}}

Is there a way to design a kickstarter campaign to increase it's
likelihood to be successful?

\hypertarget{how-you-addressed-this-problem-statement}{%
\subsubsection{How you addressed this problem
statement}\label{how-you-addressed-this-problem-statement}}

I addressed this problem statement by looking into answering 5
questions: * Are there certain types/category of campaigns that are more
successful? * How much money should you ask for? * Is there a time
period for the campaign that works better than others? * What is the
average contribution of a backer? * Is there a better time of year to
launch a campaign?

I also performed correlation and applied machine learning techniques to
see if there are ways to increase the likelihood of building successful
campaigns.

\hypertarget{analysis}{%
\subsubsection{Analysis}\label{analysis}}

\hypertarget{what-are-the-factors-that-contribute-to-sucessful-campaigns}{%
\paragraph{What are the factors that contribute to sucessful
campaigns?}\label{what-are-the-factors-that-contribute-to-sucessful-campaigns}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{# Prepping the data for modelling:}

\CommentTok{# Adding new rows to indicate successful campaigns}
\NormalTok{ks_dff <-}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{ks_dff }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}
    \DataTypeTok{successful =} \DecValTok{1}
\NormalTok{    )}

\CommentTok{# Filtering by one criterion where campaigns not successful}
\NormalTok{ks_dfn <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{filter}\NormalTok{(ks_df, state }\OperatorTok{!=}\StringTok{ "successful"}\NormalTok{)}


\CommentTok{# Adding new rows to indicate unsuccessful campaigns}
\NormalTok{ks_dfn <-}
\StringTok{  }\NormalTok{ks_dfn }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}
    \DataTypeTok{successful =} \DecValTok{0}
\NormalTok{    )}

\CommentTok{#combines successful and unsuccessful campaigns}
\NormalTok{df_union1<-}\KeywordTok{merge}\NormalTok{(ks_dff,ks_dfn,}\DataTypeTok{all=}\OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{df_union1 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{transform}\NormalTok{(df_union1, }\DataTypeTok{deadline_month =} \KeywordTok{as.integer}\NormalTok{(deadline_month), }\DataTypeTok{launched_month =} \KeywordTok{as.integer}\NormalTok{(launched_month))}

\NormalTok{model_}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{ <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{lm}\NormalTok{(successful }\OperatorTok{~}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{backers}\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{usd_pledged_real,usd_goal_real,pledged_to_goal}\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{deadline_month}\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{launched_month, }\DataTypeTok{data =}\NormalTok{ df_union1)}
\KeywordTok{summary}\NormalTok{(model_}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{conclusion}{%
\subsubsection{Conclusion}\label{conclusion}}

The best way to have a successful campaign is to increase the number of
backers for that campaign. Would not recommend campaigning during the
holiday season.
